<head ><name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aristotle</name></head>
<p ><ref  target='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/image?lookup=1997.99.0385'><figure  n='1997.99.0385.jpeg' rend='left'/></ref><date  from='-0384' to='-0322'>384-322 BCE</date> (source: <bibl ><title >OCD</title><edition >3</edition></bibl>). A philosopher, originally from <placeName  key='Stagira'>Stagira</placeName> in <placeName  key='Chalcidice'>Chalcidice</placeName>, who spent much of his career in <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>. He was a student of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Plato</name> for a time, then tutor to <name  type='person'>Philip </name>of <placeName  key='Macedon'>Macedon</placeName>’s son <name  type='person'>Alexander</name> (who would later rule in <placeName  key='Macedonia'>Macedonia</placeName> as <name  type='person'>Alexander III</name> and come to be called <soCalled ><name  type='person'>Alexander the Great</name></soCalled>), then, upon returning to <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>, the founder of a school of philosophy at the <placeName  key='Lyceum'>Lyceum</placeName>. <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Aristotle</name>’s works are diverse, including writing in philosophy, natural science, theology, and politics. (see <name  n='philosophy' type='ancientGenre'>philosophy</name>).</p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
